     1	# Fix: Lock TOCTOU → fcntl.flock
     2	
     3	## Problem
     4	
     5	`FileLockManager.acquire()` at `src/unison/lock.py:57-72` has a TOCTOU race. Between reading the lock file (line 58) and writing our PID (line 72), a concurrent process can read the same stale state — both believe they acquired the lock and both overwrite it.
     6	
     7	Additionally, `FileLockManager` supports multiple simultaneous project locks (`test_multiple_projects`). The current design tracks only a single fd, so acquiring a second lock would overwrite the first fd and leak the descriptor.
     8	
     9	## Solution
    10	
    11	Replace the check-then-write pattern with `fcntl.flock(fd, LOCK_EX | LOCK_NB)`:
    12	
    13	- **`LOCK_EX`** — kernel-enforced exclusive lock; only one process holds it at a time.
    14	- **`LOCK_NB`** — non-blocking; returns immediately with `BlockingIOError` if held.
    15	- **Auto-released** on process exit or fd close — no stale-lock cleanup needed.
    16	
    17	Track fds per-project in `self._fds: dict[str, int]` for multiple concurrent locks.
    18	
    19	**Backward compatibility**: Before attempting flock, check if the lock file already contains a live PID from a different process — if so, return False. This bridges old-style PID-only locks (pre-upgrade processes) with the new flock mechanism.
    20	
    21	**`release()` safety**: Only unlock+unlink when the project is tracked in `_fds` (we acquired it). Never unlink a lock file we didn't create. The fd dict is the authoritative ownership record — no PID-match check needed.
    22	
    23	**`is_locked()` hybrid check**: On fcntl platforms, try flock first; if it fails the lock is held. If flock succeeds (release immediately), fall back to PID check for backward compat with old-style locks.
    24	
    25	## Fallback
    26	
    27	On platforms without `fcntl` (Windows), the existing PID-based check-then-write behavior runs unchanged.
    28	
    29	## Stale lock handling
    30	
    31	With `flock`, stale locks are eliminated: the kernel releases the lock on process exit. The PID-in-file becomes metadata for diagnostics and backward compatibility only.
    32	
    33	## Acceptance Criteria
    34	
    35	- `acquire()` uses `flock` on Linux/macOS with live-PID gate before flock attempt.
    36	- `release()` only acts on projects tracked in `_fds`; never touches foreign lock files.
    37	- `is_locked()` combines flock check + PID fallback for backward compat.
    38	- All lock tests pass unchanged (`pytest tests/test_lock.py -q`).
    39	- Multiple simultaneous project locks supported (dict of fds).
    40	- Fallback to PID-based logic on Windows (no fcntl).

